New study on training to failure by Lacerda et al.⁣
⁣
Untrained men performed leg extensions with one leg going to failure and the other leg staying 0-2 reps away from failure.⁣
⁣
The non-failure leg equated volume by performing the mean rep number from the failure leg, e.g. 6 reps for 3 sets instead of 8, 6 and 4 reps per set.⁣
⁣
Both legs gained a similar amount of muscle and strength, but there was a slight trend for better gains in the non-failure group.⁣
⁣
This study supports the last review on my site on training to failure: going to complete failure is more likely to be harmful than helpful, so it's better to accumulate volume without reaching failure.⁣
⁣
You can read the previous review here: mennohenselmans.com/skeletal-muscle-fiber-adaptations-resistance-training-repetition-maximums-relative-intensity/⁣
⁣
(link in bio)

Nice new study by Cardozo et al. on exercise order.⁣
⁣
2 Groups of elderly women performed a whole-body circuit workout for 12 weeks.⁣
1. The compound group started with compound exercises in the following order: leg press, lat pulldown, knee extension, pec deck fly, calf raise and triceps extension.⁣
2. The isolation group reversed the order, starting with the isolation exercises: triceps extension, calf raise, pec deck fly, knee extension, lat pulldown and leg press.⁣
⁣
Despite minimal overlap between the exercises, the compound group gained more strength in the lat pulldown, while the isolation exercise group gained more strength in the calf raise and triceps extension exercises.⁣
⁣
In other words, the exercises they did earlier in the workout progressed better. This confirms earlier research that training adaptations are reduced by (neuromuscular) fatigue, which is also why high frequency training is good for fatigue management.⁣
⁣
Total work (weight x reps x sets) was the same between groups, as was the increase in total lean body mass. This makes sense, given that there was minimal overlap between the exercises, so only the distribution of the volume within the workout differed, not the total accumulated.⁣
⁣
I've attached a graphic from my article 3 Reasons Your Calves Aren't Growing showing you likely get more growth in the triceps when you do triceps work before the barbell bench press, but you get more pec growth when you bench first. (Also see my recent post that the bench press is probably not an optimal triceps exercise.)⁣
⁣
Take-home message: Given the same total work, do your highest priority exercises first in your workouts.

Many bodybuilders fear fructose ('fruit sugar') to the extent that they avoid fruits and sometimes even veggies. Fructose is indeed toxic, but the dose makes the poison.⁣
⁣
How much fructose is too much? A new study by Smajis et al. investigated what happens when healthy individuals consume 150 g of fructose per day for 8 weeks.⁣
⁣
The result: nothing. "Ingestion of a high dose of fructose for 8 weeks was not associated with relevant metabolic consequences in the presence of a stable energy intake."⁣
⁣
If you're healthy and your overall diet is good, you probably don't have to worry about your fructose intake.⁣
⁣
Is you're still skeptical that sugar isn't a demonic crystal that will turn your sixpack into an adipose tumor, read my article on the sweet truth of sugar: ⁣
mennohenselmans.com/sugar-sweet-truth/⁣
⁣
(link in bio)

Another nail in the coffin for post-workout ice baths and other forms of cryotherapy to 'improve recovery':⁣
⁣
"Cold‐water immersion during recovery from resistance‐type exercise lowers the capacity of the muscle to take up and/or direct dietary protein‐derived amino acids towards de novo myofibrillar protein accretion.⁣
⁣
In addition, cold‐water immersion during recovery from resistance‐type exercise lowers myofibrillar protein synthesis rates during prolonged resistance‐type exercise training.⁣
⁣
Individuals aiming to improve skeletal muscle conditioning should reconsider applying cooling as a part of their postexercise recovery strategy."⁣
⁣
New study: Fuchs et al: 10.1113/JP278996⁣

mennohenselmans.com/cns-fatigue-mike-matthews-podcast/

Going drinking during the holidays? A new study by Fisher et al. shows a meal high in fiber and protein but low in fats is a highly effective way to reduce alcohol bioavailability.⁣
⁣
The alcohol-killing optimized meal was over twice as effective per calorie to reduce blood alcohol concentrations as other meals (which were mostly junk).⁣
⁣
So if you 'have to' consume a lot of drinks, consuming a meal with a lot of protein and fiber beforehand limits the damage.⁣
⁣
This is exactly in line with my guide on how to reduce the damage from a night out drinking (see link in bio).⁣
⁣
Of course, you can also get zero damage from alcohol by not consuming any, but I realize that's not for everyone.

Strength vs. size, how different are they? According to a new study by Ferland et al., not that different.⁣
⁣
Their research topic was 'The relationship between body composition measured by Dual-Energy X-ray Absorptiometry (DEXA) and maximal strength in classic powerlifting'.⁣
⁣
The key finding was that lean body mass had a major 0.61 to 0.95 correlation with absolute and relative strength measures, including Wilks score.⁣
⁣
0.95 is almost a correlation of 1, which means we could almost skip the Powerlifting competitions altogether and just put the lifters in a DXA scan to see who's biggest, as the rankings would be almost identical.⁣
⁣
Of course, you can train more for size or for strength and Powerlifters all train for strength, so in bodybuilders the relation between mass and strength is far weaker.⁣
⁣
But the take-home message is clearly that if you want to maximize your strength potential, you can't have chicken legs.⁣

A new study by Gibson et al. finds no significant difference in satiety or energy intake between protein intakes of ~13% and ~26%, compared to the same energy intake consumed as carbs.⁣
⁣
All participants consumed ~20% of their energy intake as shakes of maltodextrin or egg protein before major meals.⁣
⁣
This study may come as a shock to those who've been told 'protein is more satiating than carbs and fats', but these findings are exactly what I argued in my article: "Is protein really more satiating than carbs and fats?" (link in bio).⁣
⁣
It's a myth that protein is universally more satiating than carbs or fats. Rather, protein leverage keeps our appetite elevated roughly until we've consumed enough protein.⁣
⁣
So there's often no point in increasing your protein intake beyond requirements for satiety. You're much better off with fibrous fruits and veggies or even often foods like potatoes.⁣
⁣
You can read the full story on the myth that protein is more satiating than carbs and fats in my article (link in bio).

Many physique athletes use a peak week to perfect their physique on the moment of their show. One component of a peak week is a carbload to fill up your muscles.⁣
⁣
The one previous study on carbloading found that it didn't enhance muscle size, but they didn't implement it well, as they likely weren't in positive enough energy balance.⁣
⁣
A new study by de Moraes et al. shows that successful carbloading can indeed significantly enhance muscle thickness and silhouette size.⁣
⁣
A successful carbload requires very scary amounts of carbohydrate. It's not uncommon to pound down hundreds of grams of carbs, sometimes over a thousand, and gain pounds of bodyweight in the process.⁣
⁣
The new study also shows that many of the athletes experienced major constipation. This is not just an inconvenience, as bloating and abdominal distension can ruin your physique. Proper macros and food choices are key to get the benefits of a carbload without these problems.⁣
⁣
These findings shouldn't come as a surprise to any contest prep coach. See the attached video for the effect of a successful carbload in my former client IFBB Pro and Ms. Olympia @bernicesangers: this is the only way to truly get visible booty gains in 1 day.

According to some research, the popular sweetener sucralose, commonly sold as Splenda, causes insulin resistance.⁣
⁣
Virtually all of this research uses extremely high dosages in rats.⁣
⁣
A new study in humans using more realistic doses by Ahmad et al. found there's probably no cause for concern. The researchers concluded:⁣
⁣
"These findings suggest that daily repeated consumption of pure sucralose or aspartame for 2 weeks had no effect on glucose metabolism among normoglycaemic adults."⁣
⁣
Note that 2 weeks may seem short as a measurement period, but blood glucose levels respond quite acutely to our diet. The one previous study in humans that found sweeteners impaired insulin sensitivity by altering our gut microbiota was only a single week in length.

Which muscles does the barbell bench press train? Everyone knows this: primarily the triceps, the delts and the pecs.⁣
⁣
But does it train all of them equally? I've attached a research overview on Facebook from my online PT Course where we looked at this. Based on the studies that measured muscle growth in the triceps and the pecs, it seems that the bench press is 78% more effective for the pecs than the triceps!⁣
⁣
That would mean the bench press is a pretty lousy triceps exercise, in contrast to what many powerlifters believe.⁣
⁣
A big limitation of the available data is that all studies are done in untrained, Japanese individuals and 3 of them come from the same research group. The execution of course also matters.⁣
⁣
Nevertheless, you most likely need triceps isolation exercises for maximal triceps growth.

We do not have a set-point and there is no such thing as metabolic damage (under any normal circumstance).⁣
⁣
This was my conclusion from my 2016 literature review together with @sciencestrength Anastasia Zinchenko published in the Medical Research Archives.⁣
⁣
Even under conditions of starvation, anorexia and bodybuilding contest prep, our metabolic rate decreases due to adaptive thermogenesis, but there is no permanent damage.⁣
⁣
Fat loss also increases our appetite. These metabolic adaptations are regulated in large part by the hormone leptin. Leptin is produced by adipose tissue (body fat), so fat loss reduces leptin levels and thereby slows down our metabolism. Gaining back the fat restores leptin production and our metabolic rate.⁣
⁣
A new review by Geary (2019) summarizes my stance well and concludes humans do not have an external set-point:⁣
⁣
"Data indicate that simple negative-feedback control accurately models human BW regulation and that the set-point concept is superfluous unless its neuroendocrine representation is found in the brain."⁣
⁣
Because there's no genetically or externally set set-point, some people refer to it as a 'settling point', but it's just an equilibrium effect we see in any system with negative feedback, so I recommend we abandon the term set-point altogether.⁣
⁣
Physically, our body fat level is primarily determined by energy balance.⁣
⁣
Behaviorally, our body fat level is the result of our lifestyle. Change your lifestyle, you change your body fat level.⁣
⁣
Nobody is doomed to be fat because of their 'set-point'. Everyone can get lean and everyone can stay lean with the proper diet, exercise and lifestyle choices.

Everyone knows free-weight squats are magically functional exercises... right?⁣
⁣
A new study by Schwarz et al. compared free-weight vs. machine-based squats for 'functional training' outcomes like agility, jumping performance and sprinting speed.⁣
⁣
Machine squats were just as effective. In fact, the data showed a trend for them to outperform free-weight squats, but this group also gained more weight, so perhaps they were consuming more protein and/or calories, as the diets were not controlled.⁣
⁣
The researchers concluded: "Machine squat training may provide performance-enhancing benefits of equal or superior value to those obtained with free-weight squat training in recreationally active women during an initial training mesocycle."⁣
⁣
One factor that made this study different than previous ones is that both groups also practiced their tested movements directly. There was also a control group that only did these sports type workouts.⁣
⁣
Interestingly, the control group that practiced only the tested movements achieved similar improvements as the groups also doing squats.⁣
⁣
This study supports the specificity principle: the most important training for any movement is doing that specific movement.⁣
⁣
Strength is priority 2, along with being lean to reduce your bodyweight.⁣
⁣
Only after that do 'functional training' considerations potentially become important, like trying to mimic your sports' movement patterns in the gym. And to the extent that these interfere with strength development, such as by standing on a bosu ball, they may even be harmful.

Should you monitor your heart rate variability (HRV) to assess when you've recovered from your workouts?

A new study by Flatt et al. says no.

After an upper body workout, changes in HRV (LnRMSSD) did not correlate with any measure of neuromuscular performance, perceived recovery status or muscle soreness across the 48 hour recovery period. Trained subjects.

It didn't matter if HRV was measured standing or lying down. The correlations were so bad some were negative when they were supposed to be positive and vice versa.

That's study nail 3 in the HRV for strength training coffin.

You might as well look at your horoscope to see if it's time to squat.

#Picturefail. I chose the photo and my marketeer put a caption on it, but it doesn't say she's pregnant, so you have to read the post to understand the conclusion.

Conventional nutrition wisdom for pregnant women is to sit on their ass and stuff themselves. That advice is as good for pregnant women as anyone else (read: it sucks).⁣
⁣
While energy intake for healthy, lean women should be increased to fuel the growth of the child, there is no reason to get fat. The mother's health strongly affects that of the child, so excess fat gain is undesirable for both mother and child.⁣
⁣
A new study by Most et al. finds that for obese women, energy intake should probably not increase above energy maintenance at all.⁣
⁣
Energy balance affected the mother's rate of fat gain but not fetal growth.⁣
⁣
Evolutionarily speaking, it makes perfect sense that energy deficit doesn't affect fetal growth. Reproducing is all that matters for our genes, so energy deficits should be fueled by the mother's energy stores, rarely compromising the child's growth.⁣
⁣
The researchers concluded: "We here provide what we believe are the first evidence-based recommendations for energy intake in pregnant women with obesity. Contrary to current recommendations, energy intake should not exceed energy expenditure."

Medium-chain trigylcerides (MCTs) are fats that increase our energy expenditure and suppress our appetite relatively much, especially for fats.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
A new study by Abe et al. finds that MCTs may also increase muscle growth and strength development, but there's a caveat. Actually, several really big caveats.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
The study was conducted in frail, elderly individuals, the diets were not perfectly controlled and the statistical significance of the results was inconsistent. For muscle growth the results were only a trend, not statistically significant.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
There's also no known mechanism whereby MCTs could increase muscle growth and strength development.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
I'm sure supplement manufacturers will eagerly cite this study as proof 'MCTs are supra-anabolic', but unless you really love coconut, I wouldn't bother adding a lot of MCTs in your diet for your gains just yet.

In a new study by Mazzulla et al. (2019), the authors suggest protein requirements are higher than previously measured.⁣
⁣
The current body of evidence strongly indicates you need only 1.6 g/kg/d of protein (0.72 g/lb/d) to maximize gains in strength and muscle mass. That's total protein intake for total bodyweight per day.⁣
⁣
This evidence includes the latest meta-analysis and a RCT study I co-authored. You can find all the studies in my article on the Optimal Protein Intake on my website.⁣
⁣
In the new study, the authors used the indicator amino acid oxidation (IAAO) technique to estimate the protein intake required to maximize whole-body protein balance.⁣
⁣
They concluded 2 g/kg/d was needed.⁣
⁣
However, the actual study measurement period was only 8 hours and directly after a full-body workout after 2 days of protein deprivation (1.2 g/g/d). So this study didn’t actually measure total daily protein requirements in normal scenarios but rather protein requirements in the immediate post-exercise period after being protein deprived.⁣
⁣
It’s also worth noting that the study had only 7 participants and 2 previous studies using the same method reached protein requirement estimates of 1.5 and 1.7 g/kg/d.⁣
⁣
Moreover, whole-body protein requirements may not coincide with muscle protein requirements. After a certain point, the requirements for maximum muscle growth may be covered, but additional protein may still stimulate protein synthesis in other tissues, such as skin, hair and organs.⁣
⁣
In conclusion, this study doesn't come close to showing we need 2 g/kg/d of protein. It rather suggests we need a correspondingly high protein intake specifically post-workout, if we didn't have that much protein in the period beforehand.⁣
⁣
In line with this evidence, I recommend higher protein intakes per meal in the anabolic window after your workouts. That's when protein synthesis levels can reach much higher levels than normal and most of your recovery and gains take place.

Recently I published a calculator on my website that allows you to estimate your natural, maximum, muscular potential and the chance someone's physique can be attained naturally.⁣
⁣
This was supposed to be accompanied by an interview from Jeff Nippard, but that won't be published, so I'll explain my methodology more on the page that contains the calculator (link in bio). ⁣
⁣
Warning: extreme data-gasm or lethal boredom ahead, depending on how nerdy you are.⁣
⁣
The calculation of men's maximum muscular potential is based on Casey Butt's extensive research published on his book Your Muscular Potential.⁣
⁣
People familiar with this work may notice this calculator gives different, generally lower, estimates than the other calculators you can find online, including on Casey Butt's own website.⁣
⁣
That's because they're based only on his first research that's available online for free. Those older formulas were based on a smaller sample size of individuals with almost exclusively top tier genetics.⁣
⁣
Moreover, the formulas were probably overfitted to the data, as the calculation for maximum arm size included not just wrist size but also ankle size, for example, which of course doesn't make much sense.⁣
⁣
The 4th edition of his work published a larger sample size with better generalized formulas. These formulas are likely to be more accurate for the average person.⁣
⁣
Although the formulas correct for body fat percentage, since fat-free mass scales considerably with body fat percentage, these estimates are only accurate for men in the body fat range of 4-12%. Fatter individuals may be able to achieve greater levels of muscularity. Sumo wrestlers actually have higher fat-free mass indices than many bodybuilders[...] (continue reading by following the link in the bio).

This may sound crazy to some, but there's a large community of people that claim the secret to fat loss is putting butter in your morning coffee.⁣
⁣
Not only that, this breakfast fat bomb is suggested to give your skin Kevlar like properties.⁣
⁣
Yes, I'm talking about Bulletproof Coffee.⁣
⁣
The idea is actually not that crazy. There is scientific backing that MCT fats in particular result in high dietary-induced thermogenesis.⁣
⁣
They also have keto-like appetite suppressive effects.⁣
⁣
So if you replace someone's usual Western junk breakfast with liquids, caffeine and MCTs, there's a good chance you'll reduce their energy intake, thereby get into energy deficit and lose body fat over time.⁣
⁣
A new study by Smith-Ryan et al. put a similar product to the test. It wasn't coffee, but it was a similar powder to create a high-fat breakfast shake with lots of MCTs, a little bit of added whey protein and supplemental fibers.⁣
⁣
The research participants consumed this product instead of their regular breakfast for 8 weeks.⁣
⁣
The result: the fatty breakfast shake group didn't lose any more fat than the group that kept consuming their regular breakfast.⁣
⁣
There is no magic bullet to get a sixpack and no fat loss product will protect you against a real bullet. If you want to get lean, you need to develop calorie awareness and achieve sustainable lifestyle change. It's hard, but it's worth it.⁣
⁣

Cool new study from my research associate Ozan Atalağ & Ezgi Sevilmiş shows that post-activation potentiation (PAP) can also be elicited by supramaximal eccentric loading.⁣
⁣
PAPA is a phenomenon whereby your strength increases after you reached very high levels of muscle activation. I sometimes implement this in advanced lifters, especially Powerlifters, after 90-100% lifting.⁣
⁣
One set-up I often use is to do a heavy single with 95-100% of 1RM for a heavy compound exercise followed by a set 1 minute later at 80% of 1RM. If you react well to PAP, you should find you can do up to several more reps after the 1RM than when you're fresh.⁣
⁣
The optimal timing varies per individual, as does the response, so using PAP is something that takes practice.⁣
⁣
The 2 key demographics I implement this in are:⁣
1. Powerlifters. If you're going to do super heavy lifting, you may as well take advantage of PAP to increase your work output in later sets.⁣
⁣
2. Advanced bodybuilders. A little bit of super heavy work has a place even for those only interested in muscle growth in my view for 2 reasons.⁣
⁣
First, it helps develop strength, which may allow you to reach higher levels of muscle activation in that muscle, and it makes progressive overload easier to measure.⁣
⁣
Second, based on motor unit modeling, the highest threshold motor units only produce maximum tension with very high loads, as then they can activate without the presence of neuromuscular fatigue (as is always the case with higher rep sets). Some very heavy work may thus help maximally develop these motor units with many type II fibers and high growth potential.⁣
⁣
If you're comfortable with heavy singles, give it a try!

Squats and deadlifts are commonly said to induce far more neuromuscular fatigue, especially central nervous system (CNS) fatigue, than other exercises.⁣
⁣
A new study by Belcher et al. finds that deadlifts induce similar total neuromuscular fatigue as squats and bench presses and take similarly long to recover from.⁣
⁣
There was in fact a trend for deadlifts to induce less neuromuscular fatigue based on markers of muscle damage and movement velocity.⁣
⁣
CNS fatigue was not directly measured but likely did not play a large role given the similar total neuromuscular fatigue.⁣
⁣
Many people have misconceptions about what causes fatigue and what fatigue is in the first place, because they don't realize there are different kinds of fatigue.⁣
⁣
- When most people talk about fatigue, they are referring to the subjective sensation thereof in the mind, i.e. psychological fatigue.⁣
⁣
- Physical fatigue in exercise science is objectively defined as a loss of force production, or performance in general, and this is mostly neuromuscular in nature.⁣
⁣
- Neuromuscular fatigue can be further separated into central vs. local fatigue.⁣
⁣
- While not a measure of fatigue, many people subjectively associate connective tissue damage and pain with fatigue.⁣
⁣
It's important to separate these different kinds of fatigue, as they have different implications and should be treated differently. Crucially, you should not base your programming decisions based merely on how you feel. Objective performance data often give a much better picture of your level of neuromuscular fatigue.⁣
⁣
Trust in facts, not feelings.

Is intermittent fasting healthier than constant daily energy restriction? A new study by Pinto et al. says no.⁣
⁣
The researchers found that 4 weeks of constant daily energy restriction had similar health effects as an isocaloric diet with 2 semi-fasting days per week in obese men and women.⁣
⁣
Measurements included insulin sensitivity and inflammation markers.⁣
⁣
The only differences were that the fasting group didn’t achieve a significant reduction in fasting blood sugar levels, but they achieved a greater reduction in fasting plasma non-esterified fatty acid concentrations.⁣
⁣
The researchers concluded the health effects of intermittent fasting are comparable to those of standard diets with the same energy intake every day.⁣
⁣
Intermittent fasting diets can offer health benefits, but most of them are the result of becoming leaner, not the fasting per se.
